# 🔌 I2C (Inter-Integrated Circuit) Protocol

**I2C (Inter-Integrated Circuit)** is a synchronous serial communication protocol developed by **Philips (now NXP)**. It is widely used to connect microcontrollers with peripheral devices such as OLED displays, sensors, EEPROMs, RTC modules, and ADC/DAC converters.

One of the main advantages of I2C is that it requires only **two communication lines**, regardless of how many devices are connected to the same bus.

---

## 📡 I2C Communication Lines

| Pin | Full Name | Function |
|:----|:----------|:---------|
| **SDA** | Serial Data | Transfers data between the master and slave devices. |
| **SCL** | Serial Clock | Carries the clock signal generated by the master device. |

---

## 🏗️ I2C Bus Structure

```text
                I2C BUS

           +----------------+
           |  Microcontroller|
           |    (Master)     |
           +----------------+
              │          │
             SDA        SCL
              │          │
──────────────┼──────────┼────────────────────
              │          │
         +----------+ +----------+ +----------+
         | OLED     | | Sensor   | | EEPROM   |
         | (Slave)  | | (Slave)  | | (Slave)  |
         +----------+ +----------+ +----------+
```

A single master can communicate with multiple slave devices using the same SDA and SCL lines.

---

## ⚙️ How I2C Works

1. The **Master** generates the clock signal on the **SCL** line.
2. The Master sends the address of the target device.
3. Every slave checks the transmitted address.
4. Only the device with the matching address responds.
5. Data is transferred over the **SDA** line.
6. Communication ends when the Master sends a **STOP** condition.

---

## 📨 Communication Sequence

```text
START

   ↓

Slave Address

   ↓

ACK

   ↓

Register Address (optional)

   ↓

ACK

   ↓

Data

   ↓

ACK

   ↓

STOP
```

---

## 👑 Master and Slave

| Device | Role |
|:-------|:-----|
| **Master** | Controls communication and generates the clock signal. |
| **Slave** | Responds only when its address is requested by the Master. |

Example:

- Arduino → Master
- OLED Display → Slave

---

## 📍 Device Addressing

Each I2C device has a unique address.

Common OLED addresses are:

| Address |
|:--------|
| `0x3C` |
| `0x3D` |

Example:

```cpp
0x3C
```

The master communicates with the OLED using its address instead of selecting it with dedicated pins.

---

## 🚀 Standard I2C Speeds

| Mode | Clock Frequency |
|:-----|----------------:|
| Standard Mode | 100 kHz |
| Fast Mode | 400 kHz |
| Fast Mode Plus | 1 MHz |
| High-Speed Mode | 3.4 MHz |

Most Arduino OLED projects operate at **100 kHz** or **400 kHz**.

---

## ✅ Advantages

- Only **two wires** are required.
- Multiple devices share the same communication bus.
- Simple hardware connections.
- Widely supported by sensors and display modules.
- Reduces the number of microcontroller pins required.

---

## ❌ Disadvantages

- Slower than SPI communication.
- Limited cable length.
- Bus capacitance limits the number of connected devices.
- Requires pull-up resistors on both SDA and SCL lines.

---

## 🔄 I2C vs SPI

| Feature | I2C | SPI |
|:---------|:---:|:---:|
| Data Lines | 2 | 4 or more |
| Clock Line | SCL | SCK |
| Device Selection | Address | Chip Select (CS) |
| Speed | Medium | High |
| Multiple Devices | By Address | One CS pin per device |
| Wiring Complexity | Simple | More Complex |

---

> [!IMPORTANT]
> ### ⚠️ SCL vs SCK
>
> Some OLED modules label the clock pin as **SCK** instead of **SCL**.
>
> **This does NOT mean the display uses SPI communication.**
>
> On many I2C OLED modules, **SCK is simply an alternative label for the I2C clock pin (SCL)**.
>
> ```text
> I2C Module
>
> SCK  =  SCL
> ```
>
> Always check whether the module is an **I2C** or **SPI** version before wiring.
>
> - **I2C:** SDA + SCL (or SCK)
> - **SPI:** MOSI + MISO + SCK + CS (+ DC, RST on many displays)

---

## 💡 Summary

```text
I2C Protocol

Master
   │
   ├── Generates Clock (SCL)
   ├── Sends Device Address
   ├── Transfers Data (SDA)
   └── Ends Communication

↓

Slave Device
   │
   ├── Receives Address
   ├── Sends ACK
   └── Exchanges Data

↓

Communication Complete
```

