# Introduction

Wireless communication has become one of the most fundamental components of embedded systems and Internet of Things (IoT) architectures. Among the numerous communication modules available for Arduino-based systems, the HC-05, HC-06, and nRF24L01 remain the most widely adopted because of their affordability, reliability, and ease of integration.

Although these modules are often grouped together by hobbyists, they are designed for fundamentally different communication paradigms. Understanding these differences enables engineers to select the optimal module for a given application rather than relying solely on popularity.

This article presents an academic yet practical overview suitable for engineering students, researchers, and embedded systems developers.

